[[File:Slab detachment.png|thumb|320px|Schematic depiction of the process of slab detachment. OC=[[oceanic crust]], OLM=oceanic lithospheric mantle, CC=[[continental crust]], CLM=continental lithospheric mantle]] In [[plate tectonics]], '''slab detachment''' or '''slab break-off''' may occur during [[continental collision|continent-continent]] or [[arc-continent]] collisions. When the [[continental margin]] of the subducting plate reaches the [[oceanic trench]] of the [[subduction|subduction zone]], the more buoyant [[continental crust]] will in normal circumstances experience only a limited amount of subduction into the asthenosphere. The [[slab pull]] forces will, however, still be present and this normally leads to the breaking off or detachment of the descending slab from the rest of the plate.<ref name="van Hunen&Allen_2011">{{Cite journal |last=van Hunen J. |last2=Allen M.B. |year=2011 |title=Continental collision and slab break-off: A comparison of 3-D numerical models with observations |url=http://eps.mcgill.ca/~courses/c350/ProbSets/vanHunen_2011_EPSL.pdf |journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters |volume=302|issue=1–2 |pages=27–37 |doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2010.11.035}}</ref> The [[isostasy|isostatic]] response to the detachment of the downgoing slab is rapid uplift. Slab detachment is also followed by the upwelling of relatively hot [[asthenosphere]] to fill the gap created, leading in many cases to [[magmatism]].<ref name="Whalen_etal_">{{Cite journal |last=Whalen J.B. |last2=McNicoll V.J. |last3=va Staal C.R. |last4=Lissenberg C.J. |last5=Longstaffe F.J. |last6=Jenner G.A. |last7=van Breeman O. |year=2006 |title=Spatial, temporal and geochemical characteristics of Silurian collision-zone magmatism, Newfoundland Appalachians: An example of a rapidly evolving magmatic system related to slab break-off |url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/academia.edu.documents/42335650/Spatial_temporal_and_geochemical_charact20160207-21893-lin7uk.pdf?AWSAccessKeyId=AKIAIWOWYYGZ2Y53UL3A&Expires=1520636122&Signature=Izkv4cftUrza%2BSVqamtCaL8%2BZOk%3D&response-content-disposition=inline%3B%20filename%3DSpatial_temporal_and_geochemical_charact.pdf |journal=Lithos |volume=89 |issue=3–4 |pages=377–404 |doi=10.1016/j.lithos.2005.12.011}}</ref>
The uncritical use of the slab-detachment model to explain disparate observations of magmatism, uplift and exhumation in continental collision zones has been criticised.<ref name="Niu_2017">{{Cite journal |last=Niu Y. |year=2017 |title=Slab breakoff: a causal mechanism or pure convenience? |url=https://ac.els-cdn.com/S2095927317301548/1-s2.0-S2095927317301548-main.pdf?_tid=1c24b9bf-69a1-4878-be9b-01b6410703e2&acdnat=1520940248_89d790b63fb9abf929e69ad041096839 |journal=Science Bulletin |volume=62 |pages=456–461 |doi=10.1016/j.scib.2017.03.015}}</ref><ref name="Garzanti_etal_2018">{{Cite journal |last=Garzanti E. |last2=Radeff G. |last3=Malusà M.G. |year=2018 |title=Slab breakoff: A critical appraisal of a geological theory as applied in space and time |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Eduardo_Garzanti/publication/321245650_Slab_breakoff_A_critical_appraisal_of_a_geological_theory_as_applied_in_space_and_time/links/5a1d3b04a6fdcc0af326be9a/Slab-breakoff-A-critical-appraisal-of-a-geological-theory-as-applied-in-space-and-time.pdf |journal=Earth-Science Reviews |volume=177 |pages=303–319 |doi=10.1016/j.earscirev.2017.11.012}}</ref>
==Slab tears== Detachment initiates at a particular point on the slab and will then propagate laterally along the descending slab, forming a slab tear. The propagation of the detachment will be accompanied by lateral migration of both the associated uplift and the magmatism.<ref name="Wortel&Spakman_2000">{{Cite journal |last=Wortel M.J.R. |last2=Spakman W. |year=2000 |title=Subduction and Slab Detachment in the Mediterranean-Carpathian Region |url=http://www.mantleplumes.org/WebDocuments/Wortel2000.pdf |journal=Science |volume=290 |pages=1910–1917 |doi=10.1126/science.290.5498.1910}}</ref> Such laterally propagating tears have been recognised from several collision zones, such as the [[Hindu Kush]] part of the Himalayan Belt.<ref name="Kufner_etal_2017">{{Cite journal |last=Kufner S.-K. |last2=Schurr B. |last3=Haberland C. |last4=Zhang Y. |last5=Saul J. |last6=Ischuk A. |last7=Oimahmadov I. |year=2017 |title=Zooming into the Hindu Kush slab break-off: A rare glimpse on the terminal stage of subduction |url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0012821X16307567 |journal=Earth and Planetary Science Letters |volume=461 |pages=127–140 |doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2016.12.043}}</ref>
